b"It's hard to blame this on a single entity.\n\nAd agencies run ads because the companies ask them to. Companies do it because they're set targets by VC firms. VC firms invest because there's growth in unregulated markets. RBI doesn't regulate because it doesn't want to stop growth."

b"India will and can be the global leader in crypto over the next ten years. 

But the fallout from ads like these will make it difficult for everybody - builders, customers, lenders and institutions. 

But agencies don't care. And they won't till proper regulations make them."

b'Mainstream adoption of crypto (everyday payments, POS support, etc) is the dream for propents of the industry.\n\nBut if 10 crore Indians simultaneously lose all or most of their money tomorrow, that dream is going to be set back years.'

b'And so with this trade-off in mind, there is a very clear incentive to make those 10 seconds as appealing and lucrative as possible.

b"Ad inventory in the IPL is expensive. 

A ten second slot costs between 14-15 lakhs. That's the annual salary for a decent engineer. 

And 15L is just the cost of running the ads. To MAKE the ad, you'll also pay for celebrity sponsorships, production, agencies, overheads, etc."

b"Back to crypto.

While I'm a huge believer in the unlimited upside of crypto, what we're doing with crypto ads is dangerous & unsustainable.

Almost unironically, ads that talk about crypto are being run alongside ads that glorify betting.

So why're these terrible ads being run?"

b'Regulations around selling "greed" are good.

Instead of being acquisition-oriented, ads are educational.

This means customers are aware of all the risks they face before entering a market.

In turn, customers participate in markets for the long-run, which is good for everyone.'
